[SkillPath "declarer_play/suit_establishment"]
[Student "S"]
{East is to play 3NT. South leads the \S4. North puts on the \SA and returns the \S8.

Winners:   \S=2  \H=1  \D=2  \C=1  Total = 6

Needing three more winners you are going to have to establish the \C suit. You are also going to have to be lucky!

You win the second \S and play your \CQ. South covers with the \CK. What do you do next?

 You <b>DUCK</b>. If you take the \CA now you will never get back to dummy to enjoy those other \Cs. So let South have the \CK. You win his return, (probably a \S), and play \CJ, then \C9 to dummy's \CA. As long as \Cs split 3-2 you will get the three winners you need.

You were prepared to lose that \C finesse to North so you could establish the suit in dummy.

South's play of the \CK may have made you want to jump up with the \CA, but you must stick to the original play of ducking one trick.}
[Play "W"]S4

